<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / Inquiry into medical fees: Carsberg referral attacks heart
of private practice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK, ANDREW ADONIS and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S consultants might have been forgiven if they collectively missed a
heartbeat yesterday when Sir Bryan Carsberg, the director general of fair
trading, announced that he was referring the fee rates charged for supply of
private medical services to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
In the last two years there has been a sharp rise in fees for private
medical work in the guidelines published by the British Medical Association,
the professional body for doctors and consultants in the UK. The guidelines
reflect the average rates for private work charged by consultants around the
country.
The referral comes at a highly sensitive time for the private health sector.
Increases in insurance premiums - which finance the bulk of activity - have
continued to outpace inflation dramatically during the recession. Some
insurers have, amid growing fears that private health could price itself out
of the reach of many of its customers, accused hospital operators of doing
too little to contain rising costs.
The BMA insists it simply issues guidelines, and does not set recommended
fee rates as stated by the OFT yesterday. But a number of medical
professionals say private consultants' fees have crept up from below the BMA
guidelines, which have become a baseline in the three years since they were
published.
The guideline fees went up by about 10.5 per cent in the 1990 BMA review,
and by about 16 per cent on many operations in the latest review published
last week.
Under the guidelines patients seeking private health treatment in the UK
might pay as little as Pounds 35 for minor ear surgery and more than Pounds
8,000 for a liver transplant involving hours of work. The schedule stresses:
'Consultants must always decide themselves on the appropriate fee for the
service provided.'
The 54-page list of guideline prices for about 1,500 medical procedures was
first produced in 1989, after several years of study by the fees working
party, created in 1985 on the instructions of its annual meeting and led by
Mr John Chawner, now chairman of the BMA consultants' committee.
Previously consultants had been guided by the list of payments approved by
BUPA, but they now appear to be increasingly guided by the BMA schedule,
which typically has higher rates.
The MMC will discover that there is little information publicly available on
how much doctors earn from private practice. BUPA - which, as one of the
largest private medical insurers, has a substantial amount of information on
the fees charged by doctors - refused to comment on the details of the
inquiry, but pledged to co-operate fully with the inquiry.
A study by the King's Fund health care think tank earlier this year
estimated that consultants in London received Pounds 175m in private
practice fees in 1989-90 - more than the Pounds 153m spent by NHS health
authorities on consultant services in the capital.
Mr William Laing, director of Laing and Buisson, a specialist medical
publisher and consultant, estimated that 12,000 of Britain's 19,000
consultants carried out private work in a market with an annual turnover of
about Pounds 500m. 'On average they earn as much from private practice in a
day as they do for the rest of the week in the NHS,' he said.
Private health care insurers have complained about the BMA guidelines since
their introduction because of the effect of increasing medical rates and
reducing fee competition. That message had filtered through to the OFT by
early this year.
Mr Roy Forman, chief executive of Private Patients Planning Group, said many
doctors had historically charged below the guideline rates and a small
number had charged more - but rates were now converging towards those in the
BMA schedule.
Mr Tim Baker, business development manager with Norwich Union Health Care,
said: 'There have been problems within the medical profession about setting
prices for a long time. And there has been pressure from medical insurers.'
Behind the OFT's referral lies a concern to contain private health charges
familiar in the US and other European countries, where insurance-based
systems have sent costs spiralling for decades.
The Office of Health Economics estimates that private health care
expenditure per head in the UK in 1990 was Pounds 88. In the US it was
Pounds 827, in Germany Pounds 290 and in France Pounds 270. The US devotes
twice as big a share of its national income to health as Britain.
Wherever healthcare is paid for by patients who claim the cost back from
insurance companies, there is an absence of downward pressure on costs. The
patient, after all, will pay any bill within reason and is unlikely to
question medical charges if the cost can be passed straight on to the
insurer.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
