<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / MMC to examine medical fees: Private insurers worried that
BMA guidelines are driving up costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE MEDICAL fees in the UK are to come under official scrutiny for the
first time in a widespread investigation by the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, yesterday asked the
MMC to investigate the way in which private medical fees are set by
consultants.
The inquiry has been prompted by concerns over guideline charges first
published by the British Medical Association in 1989. The OFT says these
'set recommended fee rates' for medical and surgical procedures, with
separate amounts for the contribution made by anaesthetists.
The BMA strongly rejected the OFT's assertion that it had laid down
recommended rates and said the guidelines reflected the average rate charged
by consultants for private work around the country. 'We have always acted in
the spirit of competition in producing these guidelines and our publication
serves the public interest,' it said.
The MMC will investigate whether a monopoly exists and, if so, whether any
aspect of the supply of these services operates against the public interest.
It now has 12 months to report to Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary.
The referral to the MMC appears partly to have been spurred by complaints
from private medical insurers that increases in costs have been driven by
the BMA guidelines.
The OFT said yesterday that the inquiry had not arisen from any specific
complaints. The announcement carried the underlying suspicion that
consultants who carry out private work and the BMA, their professional
association, may have created a fee monopoly. Health service professionals
have noticed private fees, many of which were originally below the BMA
guidelines, creeping up to the levels of the published figures since they
were introduced three years ago.
The rising fees have particularly concerned big private medical insurers
which are under growing pressure from patients demanding their services.
They claim the guidelines will have the effect of increasing medical rates
and reducing competition.
Private health care has grown rapidly during the 1980s. More than 12 per
cent of the UK population now has medical insurance which pays the bulk of
the estimated Pounds 500m charged annually by private consultants.
The OFT said that, if adhered to by a significant proportion of consultant
doctors, the BMA scales 'may affect the nature of competition and the level
of fees in the market for the supply of private medical services'.
Mr Roy Forman, chief executive of Private Patients Planning Group, said:
'All through the period since these guidelines were established we have said
that they were not advisable.'
Mr Tim Baker, business development manager with Norwich Union Health Care,
said consultants had historically used rates published by Bupa, one of the
UK's largest private insurers.
He said the rates in the BMA guidelines had generally been above the levels
published by Bupa, and prices charged by consultants had risen to the BMA
rates as a result. 'A growing number of doctors are using the BMA schedule,'
he said. 'It is gaining weight within the profession.' Mr Baker added that
the prices charged reflected a period in the past when private treatment
represented a far smaller proportion of the work of doctors. 'There needs to
be a public debate on these issues,' he said.
The announcement came only days after the BMA had carried out its second
review of the guidelines first published in 1989.
Medical inquiry, Page 7
</TEXT>
