<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / Lib Dems demand schools reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOLITION of England's local education authorities was proposed yesterday by
the Liberal Democrats, making theirs the first opposition party to accept
the end of the structure under which the schools system has been managed
since 1902.
The Liberal Democrats wish to see elected 'education departments' with
closely circumscribed responsibilities for monitoring standards, promoting
quality and strategic planning - and for arbitrating in disputes between
head teachers and school governors.
However, the party rejects the government's plan for a single national
education quango to oversee grant-maintained schools. Its departments would
be elected and based on local communities.
Mr Don Foster, the party's education spokesman, said: 'we want to increase
the independence of all schools, so that each can develop its own
distinctive ethos and style, liberated from the strictures of local
education authority control.'
The Liberal Democrats also advocate the replacement of A-levels with an
'English baccalaureate' bringing vocational and academic subjects together
in a single structure. Students at the post-16 level would study a
compulsory 'core' of English, maths, a science and a modern language.
Employers would be obliged to give all employees up to the age of 19 at
least two days a week off to study for national vocational qualifications.
A general teaching council would be established to promote the professional
status of teachers, oversee standards and advise the government.
The party calls for the school teachers' pay review body to assess
'realistically' the need for improved salaries, but rejects proposals to
link teacher appraisal to pay as the government proposes.
The party makes a commitment to increasing student numbers to 2m by the year
2000 while abolishing the student loans scheme.
Although it pledges to 'match the expansion with additional resources', the
funding implications of an increase of that order are not discussed in
detail.
Excellence for All, Liberal Democrats, 4 Cowley Street, London SW1. Pounds
4.25.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
