<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / The TUC At Blackpool: Tougher pensions law urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS are to call for a majority of occupational fund trustees to be
democratically elected or appointed by scheme members. A 'charter for
pension fund democracy' is to be launched tomorrow.
The charter will call on the government to put forward new legislation in
the wake of the Maxwell scandal. Unions argue that pensions form an
important part of the pay package so that neither contribution rates nor
benefits should be altered unilaterally by employers.
The idea of majority control by scheme members is more radical than previous
TUC proposals that half of a scheme's trustees should be made up of
employees and pensioners. Although the charter is to be launched at a fringe
meeting, and is not part of an official TUC campaign, it is being backed by
several of the largest unions.
The charter will call for a number of changes, including the separation of
pension-fund assets from the assets of employers; the right for pensioners
to be represented on trustee boards; and the right for trustees to be able
to appoint advisers to obtain independent advice.
The launch of the charter will coincide with two debates on pensions
tomorrow - one on the control of occupational schemes, and the other on the
equalisation of the state pension age for men and women. The TUC is certain
to renew its call for a common retirement age of 60.
</TEXT>
