<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / The TUC At Blackpool: Plans for sweeping reform win support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Trades Union Congress yesterday agreed a radical structural and
operational shake-up in the wake of the Conservative party's fourth
successive election victory and its proposals for further employment
legislation.
Delegates to the TUC's annual congress in Blackpool agreed to consider six
priority tasks. These include a campaign for full employment and lobbying
against planned trade union legislation.
The reforms follow a 20 per cent cut in the TUC's staff earlier this year.
Some union leaders yesterday indicated that they believed further changes
were overdue.
Mr Bill Jordan, president of the AEEU engineering workers' and electricians
union, said Congress House - the TUC's headquarters - had become an
overburdened packhorse for every social change that crossed its threshold.
'The TUC's strength is the world of work and we should play to it.'
There was no criticism of Mr Norman Willis, the TUC's general secretary, who
has been under pressure recently and expected by some to resign.
He received warm applause after his opening speech arguing the case for full
employment. 'We have to assert that unemployment is not the price we must
pay for getting the economy right, it is the price we pay for having got it
wrong.'
Mr Alan Johnson, general-secretary-elect of the UCW postal workers' union,
said there were millions of workers who would join unions if given an
opportunity.
The TUC had to tackle declining membership and its own abysmal public
profile, Mr Johnson said. It could provide a focal point for attracting
membership, particularly for people working in small organisations.
The TUC could assist in removing bureaucratic barriers to union membership
by publicising national helplines and assisting respondents in joining the
appropriate union.
Mr Barry Reamsbottom, general secretary of the CPSA Civil Service union,
said the unions did not have a 'scintilla of influence' over government
policy. 'In fact we have less influence than some pressure groups one
hundredth our size.
He added: 'Instead of constantly attacking other people's ideas, we must
produce our own.'
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU general union, said that
because the political climate had not changed last April, it was the TUC
that had to. It should concentrate on co-ordinating activities, building
strong European links and maintaining good relations between affiliates, he
said.
</TEXT>
