<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: India set for bumper cotton
crop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KUNAL BOSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CALCUTTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDIA, which accounts for nearly 22 per cent of the world area under cotton,
is expected to harvest a bumper crop of between 13m and 13.5m bales (170 kg
each) in the 1992-93 season, provided the September rains are adequate. This
is in spite of a delay in sowing because of the late arrival of the monsoon.
Crop reports from big cotton producing states like Maharashtra, Gujarat and
Madhya Pradesh, which suffered production setbacks in 1991-92 in terms of
both quantity and quality, are highly encouraging this time. The 1991-92
crop was about 12m bales.
Unlike last year, the quality of the crop in the current season will be
good.
Federal officials do not rule out the possibility of a glut and a consequent
collapse in prices in the coming months. To make matters worse, India is
opening the 1992-93 season with stocks of 3.4m bales, up from 2.27m bales at
the start of the 1991-92 season.
Government procurement agencies will have to conduct price support
operations on a large scale to protect the interest of farmers. According to
officials, while there will be considerable surplus of cotton after meeting
the mill requirement of about 10.5m bales, exporting will not be easy in
view of the low international prices and the recession in the world textile
industry. In the past, India had exported up to 1.2m bales a year, but last
year sales abroad amounted to only about 75,000 bales, including 65,000
bales of Bangladeshi cotton used mainly for making surgical grade cloth.
According to trade representatives, India must export cotton during 1992-93,
even at a loss, in order to maintain prices in the domestic market. More
often than not in recent years, Indian cotton growers have received less
than remunerative prices. The large-scale diversion of land from cotton to
other crops is not ruled out if distress selling becomes general this
season.
The textile industry, which is generally held responsible for the woes of
growers, contends that the returns from cotton cultivation will improve if
productivity is brought up to the international level. Indian productivity
of 260 kg a hectare (105 kg an acre) is less than half the world average of
550 kg a hectare, points out Mr Anil Jain, spokesman for the cotton spinning
industry.
India is keen to adopt the techniques that have enabled Israeli cotton
farming farmers to achieve an average yield of of 1,500 kg a hectare and
itrecently sent a team of experts, including the chairman of the Cotton
Corporation of India, to study that country's cultivation methods.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 32
</PAGE>
