<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRAMMER, the industrial services company, blamed depressed business
conditions for a 5.5 per cent drop in interim pre-tax profits from Pounds
4.47m to Pounds 4.22m.
Turnover slipped by 2 per cent to Pounds 56.1m (Pounds 57.1m) in the six
months to June 30, and operating profits fell to Pounds 3.91m (Pounds 4.35m)
while earnings per share fell by 7 per cent to 6.7p (7.2p). The interim
dividend was unchanged at 4.5p.
The results reflected pressure on margins in the UK bearings and power
transmission distribution business and tight margins in precision
engineering services.
There was also a small operating loss in the Texas-based Master Pumps
subsidiary due to the reduction in drilling activity. The ESE Rental
business posted a small increase in turnover and flat profits.
Net cash balances at the end of June were Pounds 6.7m compared with Pounds
2.7m in mid 1991.
Since then Brammer has acquired Roulement Service, a Strasbourg-based
bearing distribution business, for Pounds 7.3m cash, of which Pounds 1.1m is
deferred, and assumed its borrowings of about Pounds 5.2m.
