<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS difficult to believe that the wartime RAF movie The Way To The Stars
(6.00 BBC2) was made in my lifetime, since it seems part of a world long
lost in the mists of history, and yet it was - just. The evening ends with
an even better film which is four years older yet timeless: The Maltese
Falcon (11.20 BBC1). Bogart gives his best performance as Sam Spade, and
John Huston made a stunning debut as director.
In The Company Of Whales (9.00 C4) is a documentary in which conservationist
Roger Payne, who brought us the whales' 'songs', gives an update on the
global state of the whale and dolphin population. It seems like a saddening
story: the polluted oceans and a whale disease akin to Aids. Payne wonders
whether it is too late to save not only the whales but the very oceans.
The drama which follows, Gummed Labels (10.30), promises 'a bafflingly
convoluted plot' about the disappearance of a young girl, with her sister, a
detective, a psychiatrist, and a porn-movie director all looking for her.
'The audience becomes increasingly uncertain about where they are going and
who they are', we are told. Hmmm.
</TEXT>
