<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / Valleys scheme condemned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VALLEYS programme launched four years ago to revitalise the economic and
social life of south Wales has failed, according to a paper to be presented
to a Labour party conference in Neath tomorrow.
Mr Kevin Morgan and Mr Adam Price of the University of Wales College of
Cardiff, say the Pounds 800m funding was largely recycled money and had not
tackled the core problems. They call the scheme 'essentially a marketing
exercise'.
'Some of the problems the programme sought to address are as bad now as when
the initiative was launched.' New priorities are needed if south Wales is to
prosper after the recession, they argue.
Mr Morgan and Mr Price call for a firm political commitment to the
industrial valleys for the creation of a balanced economy - the valleys must
not be seen merely as commuter belts for the M4 corridor between Newport and
Llanelli.
They say the programme 'has done nothing to temper the decline in regional
policy expenditure, nothing to prevent the attrition in government support
for the the training and enterprise councils and nothing to alleviate the
chronic financial weaknesses of local government in the valleys.' The aim of
reducing unemployment by between 25,000 and 30,000 has been rendered
'hopelessly unrealistic' by the recession.
Rebuilding our Communities, University of Wales College of Cardiff, CF1 3YN.
</TEXT>
