<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / Doubts rise over pit by pit coal sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRIVATISATION of British Coal on a pit by pit basis is emerging as the
least-favoured option in the government's plans to sell the industry.
Ministers have doubts about the viability of individual pits taking on
contracts they might later be unable to fulfil.
There is also concern that National Power and PowerGen, the electricity
generators, would have an unfair advantage if they were negotiating with a
number of small individual companies.
While the present board of British Coal would like the industry privatised
intact, there are pressures on the government to privatise it in regional
units, providing greater flexibility than if the industry were left as a
single entity, even in the private sector.
Moreover, a suitable buyer for the corporation as a whole might be hard to
find.
Ministers emphasise that no final decisions have been taken about the form
in which the industry would be sold. Nothing could be decided anyway until
agreement was reached on the contracts between British Coal and the
electricity generators which will come into effect in April.
Mr Tim Eggar, then energy minister, said earlier this year that he hoped
agreement could be reached before the House of Commons dispersed in July,
but ministers are now more wary of setting a deadline.
The new contracts will inevitably be less advantageous to the industry than
those now in force. Those agreements, put in place by the government before
the electricity industry was privatised two years ago, enable British Coal
to earn almost all its money through selling 65m tonnes of coal a year to
the generators at artificially high prices.
The shape of the industry will be critically affected by the scale of the
reduction in amounts that the corporation is able to sell to the generators.
The volume of coal in the contracts is expected to be 45m tonnes in the
first year, falling to 30m in the third year and possibly less after that.
Estimates of the size of a slimmer industry range from 10 to 30 of the
existing 50 pits. Both the government and British Coal have said they are
keen to privatise the largest possible viable industry.
</TEXT>
