FT  08 SEP 92 / Some teenagers 'paid 90p an hour'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCHOOL-LEAVERS, who since 1986 have not been covered by minimum wage
legislation, are working for as little as 90p an hour, the Greater
Manchester Low Pay Unit said yesterday.
The survey was compiled because parents had complained to the unit about the
jobs their children were obliged to accept.
The unit said youngsters faced pressure to accept poorly paid jobs because
the alternatives were bleak, particularly as there were waiting lists for
Youth Training places.
'Those unable to get a Youth Training place or a better job face poverty
and/or dependence on friends and family,' the unit said. 'Income support is
no longer available to most 16 and 17 year-olds.
'They are not entitled to claim unemployment benefit, and child benefit for
young people leaving full-time education this summer will be payable only
until January 3 next year.'
Examples of low pay cited by the unit included:
A 16-year-old youth from Stockport who worked a 50-hour-week in a
supermarket for Pounds 1.40 an hour. The adult legal minimum for food shops
is Pounds 3.08p an hour.
A 16-year-old youth from Wigan whose 47 1/2 -hour week in a garage earned
him Pounds 1.26 an hour.
</TEXT>
