<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / Rover enforces immediate cut in list prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROVER is cutting the list prices of most of its cars by up to 7 per cent
with immediate effect to introduce greater 'transparency' into its new car
pricing.
The reductions will not necessarily cut the price of a new Rover car to the
customer as the company is simultaneously cutting dealer profit margins from
17 per cent to 10 per cent, which will reduce dealers' scope for
discounting.
The move is expected to cut customer 'haggling' with dealers and extends the
system introduced experimentally earlier this year for the Rover 800
executive car range.
The cuts are expected to bring list prices more into line with actual
transaction prices and reduce uncertainty over new car prices.
The Rover initiative follows initial steps taken by Vauxhall late last year
to cut dealer profit margins from 17 per cent to 10 per cent on three of its
new model ranges, the Astra, Frontera and Carlton. At the time Vauxhall said
that the industry and car buyers alike would benefit if other manufacturers
adopted a similar approach.
List prices for new cars in the UK have been far out of line with actual
transaction prices for some time, but the confusion has been exacerbated
during the recession with most carmakers launching a series of discounting
and price-cutting campaigns, often in order to sell old stock.
Rover said that its changes would reduce the list prices of some its models
by more than Pounds 1,000. The list price of a Rover 420GSi will be reduced
by Pounds 1,082 to Pounds 14,120, while the price of a Metro 1.1S will be
cut by Pounds 753 to Pounds 8,550.
Rover yesterday attacked carmakers such as Ford and Vauxhall for confusing
customers 'by offering limited discounts and other short-term incentives on
some stock, while at the same time recently increasing list prices'.
In spite of this attack Rover admitted that its dealers will also be
mounting 'special campaigns' to sell currently held stock. These campaigns
are being undertaken as part of radical changes that Rover plans for its
system of stocking and distributing cars in the UK. The aim is to cut the
number of vehicles in the pipeline and Rover believes the new system could
produce savings totalling up to Pounds 80m a year for it and its dealers.
From the end of the month it is opening a group of seven wholly-owned
regional distribution centres, which will hold most of its stock of new cars
in the UK and will remove this function from the dealer network.
The new distribution process means that Rover dealers will no longer carry
bulk stocks in their compounds, but will call up cars as they are ordered
from regional distribution centres. The dealers will carry only showroom
stock and test vehicles.
The focus of cost-cutting in the motor industry, which previously has
chiefly concerned manufacturing and engineering, is turning to distribution.
