<HEADLINE>
FT  08 SEP 92 / 6% fall in private housing starts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of new private homes started by builders fell by almost 6 per
cent during the first seven months of this year compared with the
corresponding period last year, according to figures published yesterday by
the Department of the Environment.
If this trend continued for the rest of this year the number of homes
started by private builders would be the lowest annual total for more than a
decade.
The department said starts of houses in the private sector during the three
months to the end of July were almost 9 per cent lower than in the
corresponding quarter last year.
The figures, which have been adjusted to take account of seasonal
variations, underline the deepening recession in the private housing market.
The downturn still shows no sign of slackening - almost four years after
house prices peaked in southern England.
House prices published last week by Halifax and Nationwide, the country's
two largest building societies, showed that the cost of an average UK home
has continued to fall during the summer although the rate of decline has
slackened.
Halifax warned that any recovery in prices next year would at best be muted
and would depend upon an improvement in the general economy.
The environment department said builders started work on 77,900 private
homes during the first seven months of this year compared with 82,600 in the
corresponding period last year.
During the whole of last year builders started work on 134,900 private
homes, the lowest figure for more than a decade. It compared with a peak of
221,000 recorded in 1988.
Building by housing associations, by comparison, has continued to advance
rapidly. Starts made by associations during the first seven months of this
year rose by more than half from 13,000 to 19,800. Associations are expected
by the government to take over from local authorities the central role of
providing social housing.
Overall builders started work 14,400 private and public sector homes in July
compared with 16,000 in the corresponding month last year.
</TEXT>
