FT  08 SEP 92 / Norway moves to protect currency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORWAY'S central bank raised its key overnight lending rate yesterday by one
percentage point to 11 per cent. The aim was to relieve pressure on the
krone caused by recent European interest rate rises, especially in Sweden
and Finland.
The overnight rate was last changed in September 1991 when it was raised
from 9.5 per cent. The central bank also raised the credit rate - the
interest rate the banks receive on central bank deposits - from 9 to 11 per
cent.
Mr Hermod Skaanland, Norway's central bank governor, rejected suggestions
that devaluation has been considered as an alternative to defend the krone.
He said the central bank in August bought NKr7.5bn (Pounds 682m) to support
the currency and had waited as long as it could before raising rates.
Den norske Bank, Norway's biggest bank, did not raise lending rates
yesterday but said it could not rule out a future increase.
